of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry de Radeclive was born in 1140, in Radcliffe, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir Nicholas fitzGilbert of Radeclive, was 15 and his mother, Goditha SAXON THANE BOOTH, was 18. He married Joan Margaret Booth before 1164, in Ordsall, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1190, in his hometown, at the age of 50, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1140–1190":"1140–1190","1126–Male":"1126–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1142–1205":"1142–1205","1163–Male":"1163–Surnud","1164–1220":"1164–1220","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1122–1200":"1122–1200","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1142":"1142","1163":"1163","1140":"1140","Bef 1164":"enne 1164","1205":"1205","1126":"1126","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1122":"1122","about 1163":"umbes 1163","Radcliffe Tower, Lancashire, England":"Radcliffe, Lancashire, England","Radcliffe, Lancashire, England":"Radcliffe, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Booths, Lancashire, England":"Lower Booths, Lancashire, England","Wordsall, Lancashire, England":"Ordsall, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"